		{"id":"e7b50a464afa9871","x":-94,"y":-45,"width":254,"height":105,"type":"text","text":"# Navigation"},
		{"id":"04705a94dbb29c2d","x":-920,"y":-232,"width":700,"height":480,"type":"text","text":"### 📚 Navigation Terms Summary:\n\n* **Local Navigation**:\n  Links to other pages within the same website, often embedded in text.\n\n* **Breadcrumb Navigation**:\n  A local navigation format that shows the **hierarchical path** or **user journey** to the current page.\n\n* **Table of Contents**:\n  Local navigation listing sections within the current page (or document).\n\n* **Site Map**:\n  A page that contains **links to every page** on the site, often organized hierarchically.\n\n* **Global Navigation**:\n  Links to **top-level pages**, usually consistent across all pages of a site (e.g., Home, About, Contact).\n\n---\n\n### 🌐 Global Navigation Display Types:\n\n* **Navigation Bar**: Horizontal or vertical row of main links.\n* **Drop-down Menu**: Expands when hovered or clicked to reveal sub-links.\n* **Flyout Menu**: Slides or pops out from the side, usually for submenus."},
		{"id":"35c6b0996f0c892b","x":440,"y":-632,"width":700,"height":1280,"type":"text","text":"### 📌 Breadcrumbs in HTML\n\n**Breadcrumbs** are a type of **secondary navigation** that show users where they are within a website’s structure and help them navigate back to parent sections.\n\n---\n\n### 🔹 Purpose of Breadcrumbs:\n\n* Show **site hierarchy**, not server file structure.\n* Help users **navigate to ancestor pages** without using the browser’s Back button.\n* Improve **orientation and usability**, especially on content-rich sites.\n\n---\n\n### 🔧 Recommended HTML Structure:\n\nUse a `<nav>` with `aria-label=\"breadcrumbs\"` and an ordered list (`<ol>`) to define breadcrumb navigation:\n\n```html\n<nav aria-label=\"breadcrumbs\">\n  <ol role=\"list\">\n    <li><a href=\"/\">Home</a></li>\n    <li><a href=\"/learn\">Learn</a></li>\n    <li><a href=\"/learn/html\">Learn HTML</a></li>\n    <li aria-current=\"page\">Navigation</li>\n  </ol>\n</nav>\n```\n\n* ✅ Use **`aria-current=\"page\"`** on the current page’s list item.\n* ✅ Do **not link** the current page item.\n* ✅ Use **`role=\"list\"`** for accessibility, especially if CSS affects list semantics.\n\n---\n\n### 🎨 Visuals and CSS:\n\nUse CSS for separators (e.g., arrows) between items:\n\n```css\n[aria-label^=\"breadcrumbs\" i] li + li::before {\n  content: \"\";\n  width: 8px; height: 8px;\n  border-top: 2px solid currentColor;\n  border-right: 2px solid currentColor;\n  rotate: 45deg;\n  opacity: 0.8;\n}\n```\n\n* Keep separators **hidden from screen readers**.\n* Ensure they meet **contrast accessibility** standards.\n\n---\n\n### 🚫 What to Avoid:\n\n* Avoid naming the home link as the site name or logo — use “Home”.\n* Don’t label **click history trails** as breadcrumbs.\n* Avoid duplicating breadcrumbs in different page locations."},
		{"id":"59ddf6671e5a656d","x":440,"y":-1549,"width":700,"height":792,"type":"text","text":"### 📌 Table of Contents Navigation \n\n* The **ToC** is introduced after the `<h1>` and gives a structured overview of the page.\n* On **small screens**, it appears below the heading; on **large screens**, it shows in a **right-aligned sidebar**.\n* The best semantic element for ToC is `<nav>` since it defines a **landmark role** for screen readers and search engines.\n\n---\n\n### ✅ Accessibility Best Practices\n\n* Use `aria-labelledby` with a visible heading (`<p id=\"tocTitle\">`) to **label the ToC**, instead of repeating text with `aria-label`.\n* Avoid using the word “navigation” in labels for `<nav>` since screen readers already announce it.\n* Nest navigation links in a **list (`<ul>`)** to help users know how many items are available.\n\n```html\n<nav aria-labelledby=\"tocTitle\">\n  <p id=\"tocTitle\">On this page</p>\n  <ul role=\"list\">\n    <li><a href=\"#skip\">Skip to content link</a></li>\n    <li><a href=\"#toc\">Table of contents</a></li>\n    <li><a href=\"#bc\">Page breadcrumbs</a></li>\n    <li><a href=\"#ln\">Local navigation</a></li>\n    <li><a href=\"#global\">Global navigation</a></li>\n  </ul>\n</nav>\n```\n\n---\n\n### 🚫 What to Avoid\n\n* **Don't duplicate ToC** for different layouts—it's an anti-pattern.\n* **Don’t manipulate tab order** when changing layout based on screen size. Keep navigation order predictable and accessible.\n"},
		{"id":"2f035b7a473dfd22","x":440,"y":760,"width":700,"height":280,"type":"text","text":"\n### 🔹 **Footer Navigation**\n\n* **Definition**: Appears at the bottom of all pages; **not the same** as global navigation.\n* **Content**:\n\n  * **Corporate links**: About, Careers, Legal, Privacy.\n  * **Related resources**: Contributions, Social media.\n* **This page’s example**:\n\n  * Three-column internal site navigation.\n  * Separate external links to **Google’s terms and privacy**.\n"},
		{"id":"5d491754e8f81ebf","x":440,"y":1620,"width":700,"height":480,"type":"text","text":"### 🔹 **Local Navigation**\n\n* **Definition**: Navigational links to sections within the same site or module.\n* **Display**:\n\n  * On **wide screens**: visible in a **left sidebar**.\n  * On **narrow/mobile screens**: hidden by default, accessible via the **menu** button.\n* **Features**:\n\n  * Includes a **filter bar** and **section links**.\n  * A **back arrow** on mobile screens leads to the top navigation.\n  * **Current page**:\n\n    * Should be visually distinct using **CSS**.\n    * Use `aria-current=\"page\"` and optionally `aria-selected=\"true\"` for accessibility.\n  * Example:\n\n    ```html\n    <li>\n      <a aria-current=\"page\" aria-selected=\"true\" href=\"/learn/html/navigation\">\n        Navigation\n      </a>\n    </li>\n    ```\n"},
		{"id":"eb45da253230aabd","x":440,"y":1160,"width":700,"height":360,"type":"text","text":"### 🔹 **Global Navigation**\n\n* **Definition**: Site-wide navigation appearing **consistently on every page**.\n* **Purpose**: Provides access to top-level areas across the site.\n* **Features**:\n\n  * May include:\n\n    * **Tabs**, **menus**, **search bars**, **buttons**, **titled sections**\n  * Must use `aria-current=\"page\"` for current location.\n* **Examples**:\n\n  * **Yahoo!** uses a consistent global nav across services.\n  * **Google** generally lacks top-level global nav.\n* **Accessibility**:\n\n  * Avoid low-contrast elements—ensure visual indicators (e.g., selected icons) are visible.\n"}
